Content: [telegram] <Regnar> Depending on the transaction size tbh (re @miguelborges99: Right, the first confirmation was quite instant. If you were a merchant, then how many confirmations would you wait/recommend?)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <Regnar> If I were an exchange or someone receiving large sums, I'd want at least 10. Komodo notarizations to BTC happen every 10 minutes, so while it's likely that the transaction would be notarized sooner than 10 minutes, 10 confirmations (roughly 10 minutes) would ensure it. As soon as the hash of the transaction is notarized, they can't 51% attack the chain. So if you accept large amounts of money, I'd say 10 confirmations. Smaller amounts I'd say 1, as it would cost way more to try and 51% attack, and fail anyway, just to get your $20 back

Content: [telegram] <Hermes08> Other than technical specs and way orders function , Hyperdex has a custom code that makes transactions easier to perform. It still uses market maker as Barterdex but it has some custom code added to make it way easier for users.

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <J> There‚Äôs BarterDex the core technology that facilitates atomic swaps and provides peer to peer order matching. Then there are two GUI front-ends, Hyperdex and BarterDex. It‚Äôs unfortunate the name ‚ÄúBarterDex‚Äù for the core tech shares the same name as the GUI ‚ÄúBarterDex‚Äù but it is what it is. (re @pumba2988: What's the difference between barterDEX and hyperDEX)

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <J> BarterDex GUI is a reference client that‚Äôs a bit more technical in nature and a intimidating for most users. Then there‚Äôs Hyperdex which provides a clean minimalistic design with much less clutter making it easier to setup trades for the average crypto user.
